    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="125"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d125">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Press Release Issued by the Department of State on September
                        14, 1937</hi>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d125fn1">Reprinted from Department of State,
                            <hi rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, September 18, 1937 (vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">xvii</hi>, No. 416), p. 227.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1937-09-14">September 14, 1937</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>Following a conference with the Secretary of State and the Chairman of the United
                    States Maritime Commission, the President today issued the following statement:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Merchant vessels owned by the Government of the United States will not
                            hereafter, until further notice, be permitted to transport to China or
                            Japan any of the arms, ammunition, or implements of war which were
                            listed in the President’s proclamation of May 1, 1937.<note n="2"
                                xml:id="d125fn2">Proclamation No. 2237, <hi rend="italic"
                                >ibid</hi>., May 1, 1937 (vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xvi</hi>, No.
                                396), p. 288.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>“Any other merchant vessels, flying the American flag, which attempt to
                            transport any of the listed articles to China or Japan will, until
                            further notice, do so at their own risk.</p>
                        <p>“The question of applying the Neutrality Act<note n="2a"
                                xml:id="d125fn2a">Act approved August 31, 1935, with amendments of
                                February 29, 1936, and May 1, 1937; 49 Stat. 1081, 1152, and 50
                                Stat. 121.</note> remains <hi rend="italic">in statu quo</hi>, the
                            Government policy remaining on a 24-hour basis.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
